WEBVTT

00:02.243 --> 00:03.744
<i>- The most infamous prison
on Earth.</i>

00:03.837 --> 00:07.831
- Alcatraz is the true pioneer
of the supermax prison concept.

00:07.924 --> 00:09.758
<i>- Surrounded by
the freezing waters</i>

00:09.917 --> 00:11.501
<i>of the San Francisco Bay.</i>

00:11.594 --> 00:13.762
<i>- An average prisoner
would have succumbed</i>

00:13.921 --> 00:16.256
to hypothermia
in under three hours.

00:16.349 --> 00:18.434
<i>- Four inmates think
they can beat the odds</i>

00:18.593 --> 00:20.427
<i>and make their way to freedom.</i>

00:20.520 --> 00:22.187
<i>- They were paired in twos.</i>

00:22.272 --> 00:25.766
One would keep watch
as the other did the digging.

00:25.859 --> 00:28.351
<i>- Can they escape The Rock?
- You can't look back.</i>

00:28.436 --> 00:29.945
You can't contact family.

00:30.030 --> 00:32.698
You've got to
basically disappear.

00:32.857 --> 00:39.696
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:39.781 --> 00:42.616
- Some of the greatest stories
ever told

00:42.709 --> 00:46.453
start behind bars.

00:46.537 --> 00:48.538
<i>Locked up in the
most notorious prisons</i>

00:48.623 --> 00:50.123
<i>in the world,</i>

00:50.208 --> 00:52.125
<i>spied on by guards</i>

00:52.210 --> 00:54.711
<i>and fellow prisoners.</i>

00:54.796 --> 00:57.056
<i>It takes a devious mind</i>

00:57.215 --> 00:59.800
<i>to find a way out.</i>

00:59.893 --> 01:02.719
<i>It could lead you to freedom</i>

01:02.804 --> 01:06.648
<i>or it could cost you your life.</i>

01:06.733 --> 01:09.559
<i>But wouldn't you try</i>

01:09.644 --> 01:12.404
when you have
nothing left to lose?

01:12.563 --> 01:18.068
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:18.152 --> 01:21.080
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

01:21.239 --> 01:24.166
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:24.325 --> 01:27.920
Alcatraz, The Rock.

01:28.004 --> 01:32.582
This is the most notorious
prison in American history.

01:32.667 --> 01:37.504
It's a grim concrete fortress
planted on solid rock,

01:37.597 --> 01:42.601
surrounded by the frigid waters
of San Francisco Bay.

01:42.685 --> 01:46.429
This place is always cold.

01:46.514 --> 01:49.015
And it has a way
of breaking the spirit

01:49.109 --> 01:52.111
of the most hardened criminal.

01:52.270 --> 01:54.855
Even Al Capone said,

01:54.948 --> 01:58.283
"Alcatraz has got me licked."

01:58.442 --> 02:01.695
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:01.779 --> 02:03.864
<i>- Alcatraz is the true pioneer</i>

02:03.948 --> 02:06.792
<i>of the supermax prison concept.</i>

02:06.951 --> 02:10.295
<i>- Alcatraz opened back in 1934.</i>

02:10.454 --> 02:15.208
<i>They had a huge ratio
of guards to prisoners.</i>

02:15.293 --> 02:17.136
<i>- You had, like,
this tool-proof steel</i>

02:17.295 --> 02:19.713
<i>that was touted
that nobody could use</i>

02:19.797 --> 02:22.307
<i>a regular file to file through.</i>

02:22.466 --> 02:25.310
<i>- There were remote-controlled
canisters of tear gas</i>

02:25.469 --> 02:27.896
<i>and that could be opened
in the event of a riot</i>

02:28.055 --> 02:30.140
<i>or escape attempt.</i>

02:30.224 --> 02:32.809
<i>There also was a number
of metal detectors around.</i>

02:32.894 --> 02:36.155
<i>- They were really boasting
the metal detection.</i>

02:36.239 --> 02:38.824
<i>They called it, you know,
"the invisible eye."</i>

02:38.983 --> 02:42.661
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:42.820 --> 02:45.155
<i>- The prison's construction
is unlike</i>

02:45.239 --> 02:47.991
<i>anything that had ever
been built before.</i>

02:48.084 --> 02:49.659
<i>- The cell structure is like</i>

02:49.752 --> 02:53.246
a three-tiered building
inside of a building.

02:53.331 --> 02:54.590
<i>It's three stories high</i>

02:54.749 --> 02:57.092
<i>and the cells all faced outwards</i>

02:57.177 --> 02:58.501
<i>so the guards could
walk the corridors</i>

02:58.595 --> 03:00.512
<i>and look inside
each cell as needed.</i>

03:00.671 --> 03:02.339
<i>Gun galleries up along the ends</i>

03:02.423 --> 03:06.343
<i>so guards could shoot
into the prison if needed.</i>

03:06.436 --> 03:09.104
<i>Once you're outside
the main cell building,</i>

03:09.189 --> 03:12.098
<i>there are additional fences
and 20-foot walls.</i>

03:12.183 --> 03:13.683
<i>There are thick concrete walls</i>

03:13.776 --> 03:16.361
<i>and guard towers on the corners.</i>

03:16.520 --> 03:18.280
<i>- Six watchtowers.</i>

03:18.439 --> 03:21.191
<i>Each one of them had an armed
officer in that tower.</i>

03:21.275 --> 03:23.276
This was gonna be the facility

03:23.361 --> 03:26.613
that there was no escaping,
no way out.

03:26.697 --> 03:29.041
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:29.200 --> 03:31.793
- Even if you managed
to get out of your cell,

03:31.878 --> 03:33.545
scale the walls,

03:33.630 --> 03:36.548
and evade the watchtowers,

03:36.707 --> 03:40.052
you still faced
the biggest obstacle of all:

03:40.136 --> 03:42.629
San Francisco Bay.

03:42.722 --> 03:45.641
<i>Its waters are cold enough
to kill you in an hour</i>

03:45.800 --> 03:47.643
<i>and the currents can drag you</i>

03:47.802 --> 03:50.804
<i>clean out
into the Pacific Ocean.</i>

03:50.888 --> 03:52.648
<i>- An average prisoner</i>

03:52.807 --> 03:54.557
would have
a functional time of about

03:54.651 --> 03:56.559
an hour and a half to two hours.

03:56.653 --> 03:57.894
<i>And then after that,
they'd just be</i>

03:57.987 --> 03:59.321
<i>kind of, like,
bobbing and floating</i>

03:59.405 --> 04:00.981
<i>and wouldn't be able
to really function</i>

04:01.065 --> 04:02.816
<i>and they would succumb
to hypothermia</i>

04:02.909 --> 04:05.235
<i>in about under three hours.</i>

04:05.319 --> 04:08.071
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:08.155 --> 04:12.742
- Here's how criminals
start to talk about Alcatraz.

04:12.835 --> 04:15.495
"If you don't follow
society's rules,

04:15.588 --> 04:17.172
"you go to prison.

04:17.331 --> 04:20.166
"If you don't follow
the prison rules,

04:20.260 --> 04:23.428
you end up in Alcatraz."

04:24.672 --> 04:26.923
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:27.016 --> 04:29.184
<i>- All the federal prisoners
knew if you went to Alcatraz,</i>

04:29.269 --> 04:30.519
the other prisoners
who were there

04:30.678 --> 04:32.012
were the worst of the worst

04:32.105 --> 04:33.680
in the federal prison system.

04:33.773 --> 04:37.517
- Many of the most famous
criminals of their day

04:37.601 --> 04:39.352
spent time at Alcatraz.

04:39.445 --> 04:42.114
<i>These include the infamous
Chicago crime boss,</i>

04:42.273 --> 04:43.699
<i>Al Capone.</i>

04:43.783 --> 04:46.526
<i>Other Depression era
gangster figures,</i>

04:46.610 --> 04:48.528
<i>like Machine Gun Kelly.</i>

04:48.612 --> 04:50.697
<i>Bumpy Johnson,
the Godfather of Harlem</i>

04:50.790 --> 04:52.699
spends time in Alcatraz,

04:52.792 --> 04:54.284
as does Whitey Bulger,

04:54.368 --> 04:55.869
<i>the Irish American crime boss</i>

04:55.953 --> 04:58.213
<i>turned FBI informant.</i>

04:58.372 --> 04:59.956
And of course, Robert Stroud

05:00.049 --> 05:02.467
known as
"The Birdman of Alcatraz,"

05:02.552 --> 05:03.960
<i>who was transferred
from Leavenworth</i>

05:04.045 --> 05:06.463
<i>after he killed a guard.</i>

05:06.547 --> 05:08.807
<i>- But in 1962,</i>

05:08.966 --> 05:12.385
<i>all of these big name
mobsters and murderers</i>

05:12.470 --> 05:17.474
<i>will be overshadowed by a gang
of four small-time crooks.</i>

05:17.558 --> 05:20.977
<i>It's not what they did to
get in that makes them famous.</i>

05:21.062 --> 05:24.898
<i>It's their attempt to get out.</i>

05:24.982 --> 05:28.076
- Our team of Alcatraz escapees.

05:28.235 --> 05:30.329
We have Allen West.

05:30.488 --> 05:35.917
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:36.077 --> 05:38.912
<i>- West was a--
Mostly a car thief</i>

05:39.005 --> 05:40.413
<i>and he had a lot of larceny</i>

05:40.498 --> 05:42.090
<i>and a lot of different
escape attempts.</i>

05:42.249 --> 05:44.000
<i>- He finally gets out of prison,</i>

05:44.085 --> 05:46.503
<i>goes into the military
for a short time,</i>

05:46.587 --> 05:49.172
<i>gets a dishonorable discharge,</i>

05:49.265 --> 05:51.266
back in prison,
and believe it or not

05:51.425 --> 05:54.353
ends up in Alcatraz in 1954.

05:54.512 --> 05:58.098
<i>- West is the guy who comes up
with the escape plan.</i>

05:58.191 --> 06:01.610
<i>He gets the idea while
working at his prison job.</i>

06:01.694 --> 06:03.353
<i>- West was one of the prisoners</i>

06:03.437 --> 06:05.021
<i>who was trusted
with the maintenance.</i>

06:05.106 --> 06:06.782
<i>So he would be cleaning,
he would paint,</i>

06:06.941 --> 06:08.283
<i>he would do different things.</i>

06:08.368 --> 06:10.118
There's like a seven foot gap

06:10.203 --> 06:12.362
<i>between the ceiling or roof
of the cell structure</i>

06:12.455 --> 06:14.030
<i>before you get to the bottom</i>

06:14.115 --> 06:16.616
<i>of the actual
cell building itself.</i>

06:16.700 --> 06:18.368
<i>And there's ventilation
through there,</i>

06:18.452 --> 06:20.379
<i>there's plumbing pipes,
there's wires.</i>

06:20.538 --> 06:23.206
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:23.290 --> 06:24.883
<i>While he was up on top</i>

06:25.042 --> 06:26.709
<i>cleaning the top tier
of the cell structure,</i>

06:26.803 --> 06:29.304
<i>he noticed one of the vents
was not turning</i>

06:29.463 --> 06:31.631
<i>and there's little motors
in there to pull air through</i>

06:31.715 --> 06:33.633
<i>and he's noticed
one of them was broken.</i>

06:33.717 --> 06:36.469
<i>He thought that was a way out
of the cell building.</i>

06:36.554 --> 06:39.314
<i>- That's when the wheels
start turning.</i>

06:39.473 --> 06:41.975
<i>This could be access
to the roof.</i>

06:42.059 --> 06:43.893
<i>This could be the way out.</i>

06:43.986 --> 06:45.562
<i>- West comes up
with the idea that,</i>

06:45.646 --> 06:47.313
<i>"Yeah, we can do this."</i>

06:47.407 --> 06:48.824
<i>So he knows the other people</i>

06:48.908 --> 06:50.650
who have a history of escape,

06:50.743 --> 06:52.577
and he starts talking to 'em.

06:52.736 --> 06:54.746
<i>- West starts looking
for collaborators,</i>

06:54.905 --> 06:57.157
<i>guys he can trust.</i>

06:57.250 --> 06:58.908
<i>And one man he did time with</i>

06:58.993 --> 07:01.420
<i>at the U.S. Penitentiary
in Atlanta</i>

07:01.504 --> 07:04.089
stands out above the rest.

07:04.248 --> 07:07.759
- Next on the island
we would have Frank Morris.

07:07.918 --> 07:13.673
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:13.766 --> 07:15.425
<i>He's our lone wolf.</i>

07:15.509 --> 07:17.927
<i>He's very smart.</i>

07:18.020 --> 07:21.848
- People claim Morris
had an IQ of 137.

07:21.941 --> 07:24.934
<i>- He's got the most escapes</i>

07:25.019 --> 07:27.437
<i>out of our four guys.</i>

07:27.521 --> 07:30.523
<i>- He's been incarcerated
at 11 different facilities</i>

07:30.616 --> 07:33.618
<i>from a very young age,
and Frank Morris was able to</i>

07:33.703 --> 07:36.946
successfully escape from
all 11 of those facilities.

07:37.031 --> 07:40.033
<i>- Morris recruits two
more members of the team,</i>

07:40.126 --> 07:43.953
<i>a pair of escape artists
who also served in Atlanta,</i>

07:44.038 --> 07:45.297
<i>John Anglin...</i>

07:45.456 --> 07:50.552
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:50.711 --> 07:52.304
<i>And his younger brother,
Clarence.</i>

07:52.463 --> 07:58.301
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:58.394 --> 08:00.386
<i>- John and Clarence, my uncles,</i>

08:00.480 --> 08:03.315
<i>they robbed a bank in 1958,</i>

08:03.399 --> 08:05.734
which was the biggest crime
they had ever committed.

08:05.818 --> 08:07.727
<i>They used a toy gun to do it</i>

08:07.820 --> 08:10.230
<i>because they didn't want
anybody to get hurt.</i>

08:10.314 --> 08:13.149
<i>When they went in,
the president of the bank</i>

08:13.234 --> 08:17.654
<i>got real hysterical
and he wound up passing out.</i>

08:17.747 --> 08:19.831
Well, they stopped
what they were doing

08:19.916 --> 08:23.001
<i>to get him a glass of water
to make sure that he was okay.</i>

08:23.085 --> 08:25.328
They did, you know,
tie their hands up

08:25.412 --> 08:27.664
<i>so they couldn't, you know,
call the police or whatever,</i>

08:27.757 --> 08:30.917
<i>but they never hurt anybody.</i>

08:31.001 --> 08:32.928
<i>- What the Anglin brothers</i>

08:33.087 --> 08:35.505
<i>lack in cold-hearted
criminality,</i>

08:35.589 --> 08:37.840
<i>they make up for in ingenuity</i>

08:37.934 --> 08:40.852
<i>and persistence
in escape attempts.</i>

08:41.011 --> 08:43.096
- They had the reputation
inside of the family

08:43.180 --> 08:45.765
as being their era of MacGyvers.

08:45.858 --> 08:48.860
<i>They could take nothing
and make something out of it.</i>

08:49.019 --> 08:51.437
<i>- They had tried
several different,</i>

08:51.522 --> 08:53.949
<i>and sometimes ingenious,
little escape attempts.</i>

08:54.108 --> 08:56.284
<i>Leavenworth was the main one.</i>

08:56.443 --> 08:58.111
<i>They both worked there together.</i>

08:58.204 --> 09:00.789
They had a prison camp
where they'd make bread

09:00.948 --> 09:02.865
and then they would ship it
to and from the prison,

09:02.950 --> 09:04.701
you know, and then they'd send
the empty boxes back.

09:04.794 --> 09:07.620
<i>They're large boxes,
so Clarence helped John</i>

09:07.705 --> 09:09.381
<i>hide in these big bread boxes.</i>

09:09.540 --> 09:12.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:13.127 --> 09:14.794
<i>He concealed his brother
in there,</i>

09:14.878 --> 09:15.962
<i>and then one of the guards
caught 'em</i>

09:16.046 --> 09:18.381
<i>as they were going out.</i>

09:18.474 --> 09:20.892
<i>- After their foiled
escape from Leavenworth,</i>

09:21.051 --> 09:23.895
<i>the brothers
get shipped off to Alcatraz.</i>

09:24.054 --> 09:25.471
<i>They're more than happy
to team up</i>

09:25.565 --> 09:26.806
<i>with West and Morris</i>

09:26.899 --> 09:28.900
<i>on another breakout scheme.</i>

09:29.059 --> 09:31.561
<i>- I can tell you that
John and Clarence both,</i>

09:31.645 --> 09:34.147
<i>they were always
planning escapes.</i>

09:34.231 --> 09:35.648
<i>I can assure you that</i>

09:35.741 --> 09:39.235
they were thinking
of ways to get out of there.

09:39.328 --> 09:41.404
<i>- The four prisoners
have teamed up,</i>

09:41.488 --> 09:43.656
<i>and their first task
is to get themselves</i>

09:43.749 --> 09:46.084
<i>assigned to adjacent cells.</i>

09:46.168 --> 09:48.578
<i>Given their escape record,
the Anglin brothers</i>

09:48.662 --> 09:51.339
<i>are separated
when they get to Alcatraz.</i>

09:51.498 --> 09:52.749
- So there's a really
interesting note

09:52.833 --> 09:53.842
in the case file.

09:54.001 --> 09:56.836
And the sending warden
from Leavenworth

09:56.929 --> 09:58.597
<i>makes the statement
that the two brothers</i>

09:58.756 --> 10:00.590
<i>should not be celled
next to each other.</i>

10:00.674 --> 10:02.767
<i>And they had been known
to plot escapes</i>

10:02.926 --> 10:04.510
<i>from every other facility
they'd been at</i>

10:04.595 --> 10:06.354
<i>when they were together.</i>

10:06.513 --> 10:08.440
<i>- After months of good behavior,</i>

10:08.599 --> 10:10.358
<i>the warden allows
the Anglin brothers</i>

10:10.517 --> 10:13.353
<i>to move to adjacent cells.</i>

10:13.437 --> 10:17.365
<i>West and Morris also get
locked up side by side.</i>

10:17.524 --> 10:19.451
- It took some time
to get these guys

10:19.610 --> 10:22.779
<i>nearly all lined up on B block.</i>

10:22.872 --> 10:25.206
<i>- Now that they are
all together,</i>

10:25.366 --> 10:27.876
<i>they begin formulating a plan</i>

10:28.035 --> 10:30.545
<i>to get through the roof vent,</i>

10:30.704 --> 10:32.622
<i>down the side of the building,</i>

10:32.706 --> 10:34.215
<i>past the fence,</i>

10:34.300 --> 10:36.968
<i>and across the icy cold bay.</i>

10:37.127 --> 10:39.387
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:39.546 --> 10:44.384
Step one, escape your cell.

10:44.477 --> 10:46.478
Easier said than done.

10:46.637 --> 10:50.306
The inmates know the bars
can't be cut with a saw

10:50.391 --> 10:52.400
and stepping out the door

10:52.485 --> 10:54.894
puts you directly in firing line

10:54.978 --> 10:57.989
of machine-gun-toting guards

10:58.074 --> 11:00.233
on either end.

11:00.317 --> 11:03.236
The only possible way out

11:03.329 --> 11:05.497
is somewhere else.

11:05.656 --> 11:08.166
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:08.250 --> 11:11.002
<i>- Below the sink at
the back of each cell</i>

11:11.161 --> 11:14.506
<i>is a small 6x9 inch grated vent.</i>

11:14.665 --> 11:16.675
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:16.834 --> 11:18.760
<i>And if you could actually
remove that grate,</i>

11:18.919 --> 11:21.096
<i>what it provided access to</i>

11:21.255 --> 11:22.931
<i>was a maintenance corridor</i>

11:23.015 --> 11:26.175
<i>that ran the length
of the cellblock.</i>

11:26.260 --> 11:29.095
- The concrete around
those vents was deteriorating

11:29.188 --> 11:31.189
<i>so they figured if they
could make a big enough hole,</i>

11:31.348 --> 11:35.193
<i>they could get out
of the back of the cell.</i>

11:35.352 --> 11:37.103
- The digging begins

11:37.196 --> 11:41.023
in September of 1961.

11:41.108 --> 11:44.035
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:44.194 --> 11:46.362
<i>- They stole spoons
out of the cafeteria</i>

11:46.447 --> 11:48.364
<i>and broke the tips off of 'em</i>

11:48.449 --> 11:50.041
<i>and used 'em like picks</i>

11:50.200 --> 11:53.461
<i>to pick away the concrete
around the vents.</i>

11:53.620 --> 11:55.630
- And slowly, methodically,

11:55.789 --> 11:57.540
<i>over the course of six months,</i>

11:57.624 --> 11:59.801
<i>the four men began to enlarge</i>

11:59.885 --> 12:02.962
<i>the opening
at the back of their cell.</i>

12:03.046 --> 12:05.890
<i>- Morris exploits his job
in the repair shop</i>

12:06.049 --> 12:10.061
<i>to steal a vacuum motor
and build a makeshift drill.</i>

12:10.146 --> 12:13.306
<i>They hope it will help them
break through the vent faster.</i>

12:13.390 --> 12:15.057
- West and Morris
both supposedly

12:15.151 --> 12:16.484
read a book about engineering.

12:16.643 --> 12:18.311
They said if you
use a hot plate,

12:18.395 --> 12:20.071
<i>heat the concrete up,
like, in the back</i>

12:20.230 --> 12:22.148
<i>of the cells as they're
chipping away with it,</i>

12:22.232 --> 12:23.649
they said it would help
make the concrete

12:23.734 --> 12:25.076
fall apart more easily.

12:25.235 --> 12:26.986
<i>And I think they did experiment</i>

12:27.070 --> 12:29.414
<i>for a time with that.</i>

12:29.573 --> 12:31.824
<i>- They couldn't all four
work at the same time.</i>

12:31.909 --> 12:33.418
<i>They were paired in twos.</i>

12:33.502 --> 12:35.828
<i>The Anglins
were next to each other</i>

12:35.913 --> 12:37.330
<i>and one would keep watch</i>

12:37.423 --> 12:40.675
