24:57.245 --> 24:58.654
that they're able to steal

24:58.738 --> 25:01.740
from different places
around the shop.

25:01.824 --> 25:03.242
<i>- The next big obstacle they had</i>

25:03.326 --> 25:04.576
<i>was the really cold water.</i>

25:04.661 --> 25:07.162
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:07.247 --> 25:09.256
<i>- Even with a raft
and life vests,</i>

25:09.415 --> 25:13.752
<i>San Francisco Bay can easily
kill the untrained boatmen.</i>

25:13.836 --> 25:16.755
<i>But the team finds
a surprise instructor:</i>

25:16.839 --> 25:19.758
<i>the notorious
Irish American crime boss,</i>

25:19.851 --> 25:21.843
<i>Whitey Bulger.</i>

25:21.928 --> 25:24.346
- He said that
the first time he saw John

25:24.430 --> 25:25.689
walking across the rec yard

25:25.848 --> 25:27.858
that it reminded him
of Steve McQueen.

25:28.017 --> 25:29.443
<i>He thought
they were good people.</i>

25:29.528 --> 25:31.028
<i>He thought
they were trustworthy.</i>

25:31.187 --> 25:33.364
<i>He told 'em how to
take the raincoats</i>

25:33.523 --> 25:35.440
<i>and actually make wetsuits
out of them.</i>

25:35.534 --> 25:37.952
<i>He was a scuba diver
back in the early 50s. And</i>

25:38.111 --> 25:40.704
<i>he knew that in order</i>

25:40.789 --> 25:43.448
<i>to help them survive
the cold temperatures,</i>

25:43.542 --> 25:45.450
that they would need something
to protect their skin.

25:45.544 --> 25:48.045
So he told them how to take
some of the raincoats

25:48.129 --> 25:50.381
<i>and actually wear 'em
and use 'em</i>

25:50.540 --> 25:52.299
<i>as protection against the cold.</i>

25:52.458 --> 25:54.126
<i>- He also teaches them</i>

25:54.210 --> 25:57.221
<i>how to build up endurance
to the cold water.</i>

25:57.380 --> 25:59.056
- One of the security features
of Alcatraz

25:59.215 --> 26:00.882
was that the water
that they utilized

26:00.967 --> 26:02.634
<i>in the shower area
was always very warm.</i>

26:02.719 --> 26:04.395
<i>And what they wanted to do
was make sure that</i>

26:04.554 --> 26:06.471
<i>the convicts could
never get acclimated</i>

26:06.556 --> 26:08.140
<i>to the cold waters outside.</i>

26:08.233 --> 26:10.067
<i>So that way, that if
they were somehow able</i>

26:10.151 --> 26:12.403
<i>to make it to the shore,
as soon as they hit the water,</i>

26:12.487 --> 26:15.239
<i>they would realize that they
would not be able to sustain.</i>

26:15.323 --> 26:17.149
<i>But Whitey Bulger later stated</i>

26:17.233 --> 26:20.077
<i>that some of the advice that
he gave to Clarence Anglin</i>

26:20.236 --> 26:23.322
<i>was that he was to utilize
wet towels.</i>

26:23.406 --> 26:25.157
<i>So they would actually
take these towels</i>

26:25.241 --> 26:27.418
<i>and then soak 'em
in water that was cold</i>

26:27.502 --> 26:29.328
<i>and drape the towels over them,</i>

26:29.412 --> 26:31.830
<i>and that would help them
get acclimated.</i>

26:31.914 --> 26:34.842
- He also told 'em,
"Once you make it out of here,

26:34.926 --> 26:36.251
"you can't look back.

26:36.336 --> 26:37.928
"You can't contact family.

26:38.087 --> 26:40.589
<i>You've got to
basically disappear."</i>

26:40.673 --> 26:43.350
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:43.435 --> 26:45.677
- The plan is set.

26:45.762 --> 26:48.513
The consequences are clear.

26:48.598 --> 26:52.517
On the night of June 11th, 1962,

26:52.611 --> 26:55.279
it's time to go.

27:00.869 --> 27:04.872
- On the night of June

27:05.031 --> 27:07.949
everything literally
came to a head,

27:08.043 --> 27:10.210
<i>and not just the dummy head.</i>

27:10.370 --> 27:12.630
<i>They are placing those
in the bed</i>

27:12.789 --> 27:15.624
<i>for the very last time
to fool these guards.</i>

27:15.708 --> 27:18.710
- The four men decide
that it is time to go.

27:18.803 --> 27:21.305
<i>That they're going to exit
their cells in the evening,</i>

27:21.464 --> 27:24.549
<i>make their way up
onto the roof of the prison,</i>

27:24.643 --> 27:26.051
<i>down into the yard,</i>

27:26.135 --> 27:28.479
<i>over the fence, and to safety.</i>

27:28.638 --> 27:30.481
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:30.565 --> 27:32.891
<i>- The lights out.
They get out of their cell.</i>

27:32.984 --> 27:35.477
They had a ten-hour head start

27:35.570 --> 27:37.821
before 7:00 the next morning.

27:37.980 --> 27:39.573
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:39.732 --> 27:41.992
- The officers
at that point in time

27:42.077 --> 27:44.569
probably had so much faith

27:44.654 --> 27:46.997
in the security components
of the prison

27:47.156 --> 27:49.741
<i>that they were becoming
a little bit more laxed</i>

27:49.826 --> 27:52.503
<i>and overconfident that once
they did their final count,</i>

27:52.587 --> 27:54.246
<i>there is no way that
these guys were ever gonna</i>

27:54.339 --> 27:57.174
<i>make it out of their cells.</i>

27:57.258 --> 28:01.086
<i>- They are removing
the fake grill</i>

28:01.179 --> 28:03.931
<i>and fake wall piece
from the back of their cell,</i>

28:04.090 --> 28:06.258
squeezing through that hole.

28:06.342 --> 28:08.102
<i>- But almost immediately,</i>

28:08.186 --> 28:12.431
<i>the plan and reality
start to diverge.</i>

28:12.515 --> 28:15.183
- The first hiccup
is Allen West,

28:15.268 --> 28:20.105
<i>who isn't able
to get through his vent.</i>

28:20.189 --> 28:23.692
<i>The covering that he had used
to conceal his opening</i>

28:23.776 --> 28:25.619
<i>had actually hardened.</i>

28:25.704 --> 28:27.863
- He had re-cemented
part of his cell up too much,

28:27.956 --> 28:29.865
and he couldn't get
back out of it

28:29.949 --> 28:31.032
<i>'cause he thought
he was gonna get caught</i>

28:31.126 --> 28:32.617
<i>so he kinda re-cemented it.</i>

28:32.702 --> 28:35.120
- He couldn't break through.

28:35.204 --> 28:37.122
<i>- About 9:37 that night,</i>

28:37.215 --> 28:39.458
Frank Morris came back down
and asked for a sip of water.

28:39.542 --> 28:41.385
<i>Then West claimed,
"Hey, I need help</i>

28:41.544 --> 28:43.378
<i>getting out of my cell.
Can you guys help me?"</i>

28:43.463 --> 28:44.972
<i>So Morris said,</i>

28:45.131 --> 28:46.724
<i>"I'll grab one of the other
guys and we'll come help you."</i>

28:46.808 --> 28:48.049
And then Morris never came back,

28:48.143 --> 28:49.801
so that's the last time
West saw them.

28:49.886 --> 28:52.396
<i>- And that's a really
interesting prospect.</i>

28:52.480 --> 28:56.900
If you're putting all this
time and effort into escaping,

28:56.985 --> 28:59.394
<i>wouldn't you be ready
at any time?</i>

28:59.487 --> 29:02.990
<i>And it tells us
maybe he didn't want to go.</i>

29:03.074 --> 29:04.566
<i>Maybe he was scared.</i>

29:04.659 --> 29:06.067
<i>Maybe he wanted
the bragging rights.</i>

29:06.161 --> 29:08.328
That was certainly
on brand for him.

29:08.413 --> 29:11.156
But also too,
there's another possibility,

29:11.240 --> 29:13.083
<i>maybe he was sabotaged.</i>

29:13.242 --> 29:15.577
<i>He was a wildcard,
he was a loose cannon</i>

29:15.661 --> 29:17.579
<i>and maybe they didn't tell him,</i>

29:17.672 --> 29:19.757
<i>"Hey, buddy,
tonight's the night."</i>

29:19.916 --> 29:21.666
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:21.751 --> 29:23.335
<i>- Leaving behind the instigator</i>

29:23.419 --> 29:24.586
<i>of their escape plan,</i>

29:24.670 --> 29:26.004
<i>Morris and the Anglin brothers</i>

29:26.088 --> 29:27.923
<i>race up to the workshop.</i>

29:28.007 --> 29:30.425
<i>The clock is ticking.</i>

29:30.518 --> 29:32.853
<i>- They're climbing up the pipes</i>

29:33.012 --> 29:36.106
<i>to their secret workshop
at the top of the cellblock.</i>

29:36.191 --> 29:38.859
<i>From there, they're
gathering their supplies.</i>

29:39.018 --> 29:41.770
Next, it's time
to get to the roof.

29:41.854 --> 29:45.115
<i>[tense music]</i>

29:45.274 --> 29:52.039
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:52.123 --> 29:54.115
<i>- The top vent cover
being knocked off</i>

29:54.200 --> 29:55.534
made a loud noise

29:55.627 --> 29:57.786
when they dislodged it
on the night of the escape.

29:57.870 --> 29:59.538
<i>The guards actually had a report</i>

29:59.622 --> 30:01.873
<i>at a few minutes
after 10:00 that night.</i>

30:01.958 --> 30:03.467
<i>They heard a loud bang,</i>

30:03.626 --> 30:05.210
which sounded like somebody
taking their hand

30:05.294 --> 30:07.554
and hitting the side
of a 55-gallon drum.

30:07.639 --> 30:11.975
[whistles and cheers]

30:12.134 --> 30:14.561
<i>- But their fellow inmates
come to the rescue</i>

30:14.720 --> 30:17.222
<i>with a going-away present:</i>

30:17.306 --> 30:20.150
<i>one final distraction.</i>

30:20.309 --> 30:22.653
<i>- Every prisoner in there
made so much noise</i>

30:22.812 --> 30:25.397
because they wanted to hide
where that noise came from.

30:25.490 --> 30:28.900
<i>- The escapees are finally
through the ventilation grate</i>

30:28.993 --> 30:31.987
<i>and up on the roof.</i>

30:32.080 --> 30:33.822
<i>- And they had no idea
what the actual roof</i>

30:33.915 --> 30:35.249
<i>of the building looked like</i>

30:35.408 --> 30:36.750
<i>'cause nobody got
to go up there.</i>

30:36.835 --> 30:38.493
- I always think that
that must have been

30:38.578 --> 30:40.579
such an amazing feeling

30:40.663 --> 30:43.006
to finally make it
onto the roof,

30:43.165 --> 30:44.675
<i>having never seen</i>

30:44.834 --> 30:46.760
<i>the cityscape
of San Francisco at night</i>

30:46.919 --> 30:49.847
<i>without any bars or barriers.</i>

30:50.006 --> 30:52.340
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:52.425 --> 30:54.601
<i>- They're able
to go up to the roof.</i>

30:54.686 --> 30:56.186
First, an inmate goes up

30:56.271 --> 30:58.513
and next,
the supplies need to come up.

30:58.606 --> 31:00.515
<i>The supplies that are coming up</i>

31:00.608 --> 31:03.685
<i>through that air shaft
are paddles,</i>

31:03.769 --> 31:05.854
<i>the inflatables,</i>

31:05.938 --> 31:07.865
<i>a concertina.</i>

31:08.024 --> 31:11.359
A concertina is not
the same as an accordion,

31:11.452 --> 31:13.370
but it is in the same family.

31:13.529 --> 31:18.792
A concertina added a benefit
because of its valve system.

31:18.951 --> 31:21.545
<i>The way it forces air out</i>

31:21.704 --> 31:27.125
would make for a great way
to inflate a raft.

31:27.209 --> 31:29.219
<i>- Carrying all their gear,</i>

31:29.304 --> 31:32.964
<i>the three men dash 100 feet
to the edge of the roof,</i>

31:33.057 --> 31:37.227
<i>careful to avoid being spotted
by the guard towers.</i>

31:37.386 --> 31:41.556
<i>They are now face to face
with their next obstacle:</i>

31:41.641 --> 31:43.642
<i>getting down.</i>

31:43.735 --> 31:46.561
<i>- They're going to have to
go down 35, 40 feet probably.</i>

31:46.646 --> 31:48.822
<i>They work their way
to the north-northwest side</i>

31:48.907 --> 31:50.899
<i>of the cell building</i>

31:50.983 --> 31:52.734
and there's a stovepipe
back there for the kitchen.

31:52.827 --> 31:54.745
<i>- Months of planning
and hard work</i>

31:54.829 --> 31:57.915
<i>and subterfuge will have
all been for nothing</i>

31:58.074 --> 32:01.501
<i>if they can't make it down
this rickety pipe.</i>

32:01.586 --> 32:04.421
<i>No turning back now.</i>

32:04.580 --> 32:07.215
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:12.171 --> 32:15.256
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

32:15.341 --> 32:17.926
<i>- Inmates Frank Morris,
Clarence Anglin,</i>

32:18.010 --> 32:19.761
<i>and his brother John,</i>

32:19.845 --> 32:22.856
<i>are on the precipice of freedom,</i>

32:22.941 --> 32:25.934
<i>staring down
from the roof of Alcatraz</i>

32:26.027 --> 32:29.529
<i>to the ground 40 feet below.</i>

32:29.689 --> 32:32.941
<i>One slip here would be fatal.</i>

32:33.025 --> 32:35.702
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:35.861 --> 32:38.538
- They end up shimmying down
a chimney

32:38.698 --> 32:42.200
that goes down
to the prison bakery.

32:42.284 --> 32:44.953
<i>- They kind of used it
like a fireman does on a pole.</i>

32:45.046 --> 32:48.289
They wrapped around it
and slid down it.

32:48.383 --> 32:50.133
<i>- It was really rusty and sooty.</i>

32:50.292 --> 32:53.136
And we know they used that
because at the bottom,

32:53.221 --> 32:55.389
<i>after the escape,
the next day they have photos</i>

32:55.473 --> 32:57.132
<i>and there's a whole bunch
of sooty footprints</i>

32:57.225 --> 32:59.059
<i>all along the ground
on the bottom</i>

32:59.143 --> 33:01.395
where they shimmied
their way down the pipe.

33:01.479 --> 33:04.723
<i>- They had acquired
an extension cord</i>

33:04.807 --> 33:07.150
that was 125 foot long.

33:07.309 --> 33:08.735
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:08.894 --> 33:10.812
- They used that extension cord

33:10.905 --> 33:12.981
<i>to lower their gear
from the roof.</i>

33:13.074 --> 33:14.574
<i>- Once they were down there</i>

33:14.734 --> 33:15.984
and had all their stuff
down there,

33:16.077 --> 33:19.404
they still had a probably
15-foot fence to get over.

33:19.497 --> 33:22.157
- They took a blanket and
laid it over the barbed wire

33:22.241 --> 33:24.743
so it wouldn't cut 'em
as they were going across it.

33:24.827 --> 33:26.578
<i>- They were able
to climb over the fence</i>

33:26.671 --> 33:28.505
<i>and they could see a spot
where the barbed wire</i>

33:28.589 --> 33:30.915
<i>was pushed down
and they actually could see</i>

33:31.009 --> 33:32.917
<i>where they worked their way
through down the hill,</i>

33:33.011 --> 33:34.344
<i>underneath the water tower.</i>

33:34.503 --> 33:35.846
And they know they went down
that way 'cause they found

33:35.930 --> 33:37.505
a coiled up extension cord

33:37.598 --> 33:39.016
right at the bottom
of that slope.

33:39.100 --> 33:41.351
<i>And then from there, they
know they worked their way</i>

33:41.510 --> 33:43.428
<i>basically to the
northwest side of the island</i>

33:43.512 --> 33:45.597
<i>which was the closest
launching point</i>

33:45.681 --> 33:47.107
<i>for their destination,</i>

33:47.191 --> 33:50.861
which West claimed
was Angel Island.

33:51.020 --> 33:52.437
<i>They didn't want to go
towards San Francisco</i>

33:52.521 --> 33:53.772
<i>because too many people there,</i>

33:53.856 --> 33:55.023
<i>too many people would see 'em,</i>

33:55.107 --> 33:56.533
<i>and it'd be too hard
for them to blend in</i>

33:56.617 --> 33:59.694
<i>or to easily be seen
by local police.</i>

33:59.787 --> 34:02.372
They knew Angel Island
was largely unoccupied.

34:02.531 --> 34:04.282
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:04.366 --> 34:06.785
<i>And they knew
it was a missile base</i>

34:06.869 --> 34:08.462
<i>back in the '50s and '60s</i>

34:08.546 --> 34:09.880
<i>and it was starting
to be deactivated</i>

34:10.039 --> 34:12.457
<i>so there were probably
a few Army personnel there,</i>

34:12.550 --> 34:14.542
<i>but they assumed that there
are gonna be boats there.</i>

34:14.627 --> 34:16.628
<i>They were actually gonna
be able to get a real boat</i>

34:16.712 --> 34:18.797
<i>and get to the mainland.</i>

34:18.890 --> 34:23.226
- Multiple stages of the escape
seem improbable.

34:23.385 --> 34:27.889
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:27.973 --> 34:29.891
<i>The idea that these men</i>

34:29.984 --> 34:32.060
<i>could leave their cells
in the night</i>

34:32.144 --> 34:33.820
<i>for weeks on end</i>

34:33.905 --> 34:35.647
<i>and not be detected, for one,</i>

34:35.740 --> 34:37.074
<i>given the security measures</i>

34:37.233 --> 34:39.826
<i>that we know
were in place in Alcatraz.</i>

34:39.985 --> 34:44.581
<i>And then simply making it
from outside of the prison</i>

34:44.740 --> 34:47.492
<i>and to the shore,
that itself is not a given</i>

34:47.576 --> 34:50.170
and that's part of the escape
that they're not able to scout

34:50.254 --> 34:51.922
and plan with the same precision

34:52.081 --> 34:55.667
as they are the construction
of, say, their raft.

34:55.760 --> 34:57.752
<i>- Against all odds,</i>

34:57.837 --> 34:59.596
<i>they make it to the shore.</i>

34:59.680 --> 35:02.516
<i>They inflate the raft
with the concertina</i>

35:02.675 --> 35:04.092
<i>and push off into the dark</i>

35:04.185 --> 35:06.678
<i>and treacherous waters
of the bay.</i>

35:06.771 --> 35:09.272
<i>[uneasy music]</i>

35:09.431 --> 35:14.936
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:15.029 --> 35:17.021
- No guard notices
any of them are gone

35:17.106 --> 35:18.857
until the next morning.

35:18.941 --> 35:21.618
<i>- 7:00 headcount,
those three cells,</i>

35:21.702 --> 35:23.945
<i>Morris and my uncles,
the Anglin brothers,</i>

35:24.029 --> 35:26.781
they did not come out
of their cells for headcount.

35:26.874 --> 35:28.291
<i>So one of the guards goes by</i>

35:28.376 --> 35:30.544
<i>and takes his little
walking stick</i>

35:30.703 --> 35:32.462
<i>and taps them on the head.</i>

35:32.621 --> 35:34.548
<i>- And he wouldn't wake up,
and when they</i>

35:34.632 --> 35:36.633
tapped on the head
they said, "He's dead."

35:36.792 --> 35:38.552
Initially said,
"I think he's dead."

35:38.711 --> 35:40.137
They started hitting harder.

35:40.296 --> 35:42.046
<i>- Then that's when
one of the heads</i>

35:42.140 --> 35:44.215
<i>fell out on the floor and
it kind of freaked him out.</i>

35:44.308 --> 35:46.309
<i>He thought somebody had
cut his head off, you know?</i>

35:46.394 --> 35:48.562
<i>He went screaming,
and that's when they realized</i>

35:48.646 --> 35:50.471
<i>that they were gone.</i>

35:50.565 --> 35:51.806
[alarm blares, whistle blows]

35:51.899 --> 35:54.642
<i>- And they called it out,
"Sound the alarm."</i>

35:54.735 --> 35:56.728
<i>- Whitey Bulger told us
when they discovered</i>

35:56.812 --> 35:59.990
<i>that they were missing
and the sirens went off,</i>

36:00.074 --> 36:02.734
<i>he said everybody in the cell
block just went to cheering</i>

36:02.818 --> 36:04.911
<i>'cause they knew
that they had made it.</i>

36:04.996 --> 36:07.822
He said it was a great moment
in his life.

36:07.907 --> 36:09.166
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:09.325 --> 36:10.658
- Morris and the Anglin brothers

36:10.751 --> 36:14.913
have successfully launched
two things:

36:15.006 --> 36:17.090
their escape raft

36:17.249 --> 36:20.510
and one of the biggest
manhunts ever.

36:20.669 --> 36:24.014
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:29.178 --> 36:31.271
[siren blares, whistle blows]

36:31.355 --> 36:34.432
<i>- On the morning
of June 12th, 1962,</i>

36:34.525 --> 36:37.518
<i>all hell breaks loose
when guards discover</i>

36:37.603 --> 36:40.772
<i>that Frank Morris
and the Anglin brothers</i>

36:40.865 --> 36:43.200
<i>have vanished.</i>

36:43.359 --> 36:45.944
- They just started
searching everywhere for them.

36:46.037 --> 36:48.622
<i>- They say it was
one of the largest manhunts</i>

36:48.781 --> 36:50.123
in history at the time.

36:50.208 --> 36:52.700
<i>- And FBI came out and
they called the Coast Guard.</i>

